## Part II — Architecture Assessment

### The Fundamental Problem: Two Disconnected Services

The API and realtime service have **zero connection** to each other. They do not share a database, do not communicate via events, do not share a JWT secret, and do not share type definitions. They are not a platform — they are two separate applications that happen to serve the same product.

```
Current (broken) architecture:

Client ──→ backend/api        (REST, Postgres, TypeScript, auth-free)
Client ──→ backend/realtime   (WS,   in-memory,  JavaScript, auth-free)
            ↑
            No connection between them
```

```
Target architecture:

Client ──→ backend/api        (REST, Postgres, business logic, auth authority)
               │
               │ publishes domain events
               ↓
           Redis Pub/Sub
               │
               │ consumes events, delivers to connected clients
               ↓
Client ←── backend/realtime   (WS, delivery only, auth via JWT from API)
```

### Service Responsibility Boundary (Final)

This is the single source of truth for what each service owns.

| Responsibility | Owner | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| User registration / login | API | Issues JWT |
| JWT issuance and verification | API | Realtime verifies, API issues |
| Session management | API | Persistent, in Postgres |
| User profile management | API | |
| Connection requests / acceptance | API | Persists in Postgres |
| Conversation creation | API | |
| Message persistence | API | Writes to `Message` table |
| Identity reveal state machine | API | Persists `IdentityState` on `Participant` |
| Policy enforcement | API | `PolicyService.assertCapability()` |
| Business rule validation | API | All business logic |
| Real-time message delivery | Realtime | Receives via Redis, delivers to WS clients |
| Presence tracking (online/offline) | Realtime | Tracks connected clients |
| Matchmaking queue | Realtime | In-memory queue + interest scoring |
| Typing indicators | Realtime | In-memory, ephemeral |
| Read receipt delivery | Realtime | Delivery only; persistence in API |
| Room management | Realtime | Maps conversation IDs to WS client sets |
| Reconnection grace period | Realtime | Client reconnect within window |
| Heartbeat / connection health | Realtime | Ping/pong |

**The critical rule**: The realtime service **never** writes to the database. The API **never** pushes to WebSocket clients directly. Communication flows through Redis Pub/Sub.

