## Part IV — API ↔ Realtime Communication Architecture

### Communication Pattern: Redis Pub/Sub

```
[Client]                [API]                  [Redis]           [Realtime]
   │                      │                       │                   │
   │─── POST /messages ──→│                       │                   │
   │                      │── persist to DB ──────│                   │
   │                      │── PUBLISH msg.sent ──→│                   │
   │                      │                       │── SUBSCRIBE ──────│
   │                      │                       │     event ────────→│
   │                      │                       │                   │── ws.send() ──→[Client]
   │                      │                       │                   │── ws.send() ──→[Partner]
```

### Channel Naming Convention

```
# Format: moots:{domain}:{event_type}
moots:messages:sent
moots:messages:deleted
moots:messages:edited
moots:reactions:updated
moots:conversations:created
moots:participants:typing
moots:participants:read
moots:identity:reveal_initiated
moots:identity:reveal_confirmed
moots:connections:requested
moots:connections:accepted
moots:presence:online
moots:presence:offline
moots:matchmaking:matched
```

### Redis Event Envelope

```typescript
// packages/contracts/src/events.ts (shared package)

interface PlatformEvent<T> {
  eventId:       string;       // CUID2 — unique event ID for deduplication
  eventType:     string;       // 'messages.sent'
  version:       1;            // schema version — increment on breaking changes
  occurredAt:    string;       // ISO-8601
  conversationId?: string;     // routing hint for the realtime service
  userId?:       string;       // target user for direct delivery
  payload:       T;
}
```

### Internal API Endpoints (Realtime → API)

When the realtime service needs to trigger business logic (e.g., persist a message), it calls internal API endpoints. These are not public-facing and require an `X-Internal-Service-Key` header.

```
POST /internal/v1/messages          # persist a sent message
POST /internal/v1/conversations/:id/read   # mark messages as read
POST /internal/v1/connections        # create connection request
PATCH /internal/v1/conversations/:id/reveal # initiate identity reveal
```

Secured by a shared `INTERNAL_SERVICE_KEY` (rotating secret, not exposed publicly).

**Alternative**: The realtime service publishes a Redis command event, the API consumes it, persists, and re-publishes the result event. This keeps the API as the sole HTTP consumer of Postgres, avoiding any HTTP call chain.

### Authentication Propagation

```
1. Client authenticates with API → receives JWT (access + refresh)
2. Client opens WS connection: ws://realtime.moots.in?token=<JWT>
3. Realtime service verifies JWT using shared JWT_SECRET
4. userId extracted from token claims — never from message payload
5. userId stored in ConnectionRegistry for the lifetime of the connection
6. All subsequent messages use registry.get(connectionId).userId
```

### Request Correlation Across Services

```typescript
// Every platform event carries a correlationId
interface PlatformEvent<T> {
  correlationId: string;  // requestId from the originating HTTP request
  // ...
}

// Realtime log entries include correlationId when processing events
logger.info('Delivering message event', {
  correlationId: event.correlationId,
  eventId: event.eventId,
  conversationId: event.conversationId,
});
```

This enables end-to-end tracing: a message send request in the API can be traced through Redis delivery to the WS push.

