## Part XI — Long-Term Bounded Contexts & Evolution (v2)

While Phases 1–7 establish a secure, scalable, and correct platform, the ultimate architecture to support millions of users and future entities (e.g. AI assistants, organizations) will evolve toward these strict bounded contexts:

### 1. Universal Actor Model
`Actor` becomes the universal root for all identities: `USER`, `GUEST`, `BOT`, `SYSTEM`, `MODERATOR`, `SUPPORT`, `AI`, `ORGANIZATION`. This prevents future schema migrations when adding new participant types.

### 2. Dedicated Persona Entity
`Persona` becomes a concrete database entity (`id, participantId, displayName, avatar, theme, accentColor, badge`). This decouples UI representation from the `Actor` entirely, crucial for customizable anonymous identities.

### 3. Formalized Identity State Machine
`IdentityState` transitions strictly from `HIDDEN → REVEAL_PENDING → REVEALED → REVOKED`, preventing impossible states at the database level.

### 4. Participant-based Connections
`Connection` links `Participant` to `Participant`, not `Actor` to `Actor`. Connections belong to the context of a conversation, allowing one person with multiple identities to maintain strict boundary separation.

### 5. Immutable Conversations
`Conversation` state becomes derived. Instead of mutative statuses (`ACTIVE`, `CLOSED`), conversations are immutable ledgers with `createdAt`, `endedAt`, and `deletedAt`.

### 6. Event Sourcing & Domain Events
Every mutation produces a `DomainEvent` (`id, aggregateId, aggregateType, eventType, payload, occurredAt`). This enables replay, CQRS, audit logs, and decoupling without redesign.

### 7. Data-Driven Policies
Policies (e.g. `GUEST_POLICY`) move from code to database entities (`Policy: id, name, capabilities, retention, identityRules`). `Conversation` instances reference a `policyId`.

### 8. Strict Asynchronous Communication
Realtime drops **all** internal HTTP calls to the API. Instead: `Realtime → Redis Command Queue → API Worker → Postgres → Redis Pub/Sub Event → Realtime`.

### 9. Strict Participant Ownership
`Message` relies exclusively on `senderParticipantId`. It never knows about `actorId` or `userId`.

### 10. Dedicated Presence Domain
Presence becomes a standalone domain (`lastSeen, online, device, status, typing`). The Realtime service merely updates it; the Presence domain owns the source of truth.

### 11. Concrete Device Entities
`Device` becomes a core model (`id, actorId, deviceId, platform, pushToken, fingerprint, trusted`) to support multi-device push notifications and login anomaly detection.

### 12. Session Segregation
`Session` is split into `AuthenticationSession` (login tokens) and `ConversationSession` (active participation in a room).

### 13. Aggregate Roots
Repositories strictly enforce Aggregate Roots (e.g. `Conversation` owns `Participant`, `Persona`, `Messages`). Repositories only fetch and persist whole aggregates.

### 14. Outbox Pattern for Redis
To guarantee message delivery without lost events, transactions write the message to Postgres and a `DomainEvent` to an Outbox table in the same transaction. A dedicated worker publishes the outbox to Redis.

### 15. Complete Capability-Based Authorization
No hardcoded `if (isGuest)` checks anywhere. All operations pass through `policy.can(Capability, actor, conversation)`.

